Installation of Firebase

5 steps

Traditionally, any application that requires passing of data will require its own dedicated server. Serverless computing allows you to build scalable applications that can be run on one or more machines without any intervention. That is essentially Firebase. With Firebase, your projects will have a unique domain. It is fast and efficient.

To enjoy the full benefits of Firebase, we will first need to install the Firebase tools. In this tutorial, we will dive deeper into the purpose and functions of Firebase. We will also install the necessary tools for us to integrate with our development workflow!
Join us on Discord

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  1. Discover the functionality of Firebase and the other services it offer
  2. Install Firebase tools on your local machine
  3. Create a Firebase Account with Google and use the Firebase platform effectively

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: What is Firebase and Why Should I Learn It?

    Before we start installing the necessary tools needed for us to use Firebase, watch the video above. Firebase is more than just a hosting service. It also has a wide range of features and functions you need to get started with your project.

    We will be diving deeper into the limits of Firebase and what it can do. Firebase is powerful with a wide range of tools to help us in our dream projects. Next, read this article on Firebase. This article outlines the types of functions and features that Firebase has to offer and why it is breaking new grounds for developers like us.

    🔗What is Firebase?

    Finally, let us dive deeper into the Hosting our Web App on Firebase by reading the article below. The article will show us the process and procedures of hosting our applications using the Command Line Interface (CLI). This article will also show the types of files we are dealing with and how everything works as a whole.

    🔗Publishing Web Apps to Firebase

    While you read this article, a few questions you can think about

    • What is Firebase good for?
    • How can you use Firebase to your advantage?
    • What are the features you can use in Firebase?
    • Why is Firebase powerful against conventional deployment?
  • Step 2: Creating An Account With Firebase

    Firebase is a Google product. All you need is to have a Google Account. If you do not have an account with Google, you may create one here. You will need to follow the steps in the website to create your own Google Account.

    Next, head to the Firebase platform.

    On the top right-hand corner of this webpage, there will be a button that says “Go to Console”. Click on it and it will direct you to your dashboard on Firebase. If you are not redirected there, you will need to first log in to your Google Account. This Google Account can be your own personal account or the account you have just created.

    Great! We are now ready to install the Firebase tools.

  • Step 3: Installation of Node JS

    In this step, we will be installing the tools we need for Firebase. Firstly, we need to install a JavaScript Package manager called Node. This will allow us to install Firebase Tools onto our machine. Head here to install Node onto your machine.

    Select the installer for the machine’s operating system. It will install an executable installer for seamless installation. Run the installer.

    Once you have opened the installer, follow the on-screen steps to safely install the file onto your machine. Node will then install some packages for you to install dependencies for any JavaScript project you may have.

  • Step 4: Firebase Tools CLI

    Finally, we are almost done with setting up our environment for Firebase. We will need to install the final component and that is the Firebase CLI Tools. For us to upload files, deploy files for hosting, and initialise the project as a Firebase project, we will need to do so via the Command Line Interface. This is the same for all operating systems.

    Open your native terminal or command prompt and enter this command

    npm install -g firebase-tools

    Do remember this command as it is the standard command used for all JavaScript projects that require Node’s dependencies files. The first word: npm means Node Package Manager and for most command line tools, the first word is usually the program or app responsible for that command. The next word install is the command for that particular program. For this case, relevant packages will be downloaded and installed onto our machine. Next is -g which is known as a flag. Flags are additional commands which can be added to the current command function. In this case, -g for node stands for global. Any packages installed in this will be stored in a global directory in your local machine. This means that any project that requires this package can make reference to this package without having to install it in the future. Lastly, the package name. For this case, it is firebase-tools. Node will look at its directory of packages and find the one with this package name and download it.

    Do remember this as we will use it frequently in other JavaScript projects that will require Node installation.

    Once you are done with the installation process, we will need you to enter the next command into your terminal to prove that you have properly completed the installation of Firebase tools.

    firebase -V

    This means that “firebase” is now the program responsible for this command and “-V” means the current installed version number of Firebase tools.

    Some users may face privileged restrictions or errors. This is due to Node installing Firebase into a folder which requires administrator privileges. This can be solved by doing the following:

    For Window users:

    Open Command Prompt as Administrator.

    Run the previous code, you should be able to run it now.

    For MacOS and Linux users:

    Type the following code into your terminal

    sudo firebase -V

    Sudo stands for Super User which will prompt you to enter the administrator’s password to allow the necessary tools to run.

    We have finally completed the setup of our Firebase Tools.
